esidents uniformly call for more humane and dignified treatment. Staff yearn for more expansive control. But, as Rudes shows, there also remains fierce resilience among residents and staff and across the communities they forge—and a perpetual hope that they may have a different future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aPrisonerszUnited States. 0aPrisonszUnited StatesxOfficials and employees. 0aSolitary confinementzUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  acarceral residents.  acorrectional staff.  ainterviews.  aprison reform.  aprisons.  aqualitative.  areentry.  arestricted housing units.  asolitary confinement.1 aHattery, Angela.1 aMagnuson, Shannon.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631243423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631243/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles